name: So-Young Kang
text: A6. Critical. Women need to support other women. And we all need networks to support and actively promote each other - women and men. Networks can provide exposure, connections, mentors, potential clients, partners, etc. #EVELeadershipChat @programmeeve

name: So-Young Kang
text: @LewisGarrad @ProgrammeEVE The underlying beliefs and values in the sub-conscious are critical to uncover to help people address the behaviors. For example, in a meeting room, just by asking men to count the # of times women get interrupted vs. men would start to address unconscious bias.

name: So-Young Kang
text: @ProgrammeEVE Building men's confidence levels so that they don't feel intimidated by a successful partner. This is key to start with young boys and as they grow to show role models of successful working women, moms, and wives. #eveleadershipchat @ProgrammeEVE

name: So-Young Kang
text: @ProgrammeEVE A4. Gender-neutral pay, performance management and exposure opportunities. Need to be aware of unconscious bias and train people to be more conscious of what happens during meetings and when women speak to give women chance to be heard and seen. @ProgrammeEVE #EVELeadershipchat

name: So-Young Kang
text: @kfravil @ProgrammeEVE Agree. Many women sometimes don't know what the options are. Picking each other up and actively seeking opportunities to support others is also important.

name: So-Young Kang
text: @ProgrammeEVE A3. Corporates can actively develop both women and men by redefining effective leadership qualities which will show that it's not about gender and then create role models for women to see. #eveleadershipchat @ProgrammeEVE

name: So-Young Kang
text: @LouiseTagliante @ProgrammeEVE Agree with you. We need to encourage women to be bold and stand up for what they believe. Confidence building is key.

name: So-Young Kang
text: @ginaheng80 @ProgrammeEVE yes agree. it should be about effectiveness, not # of hours.

name: So-Young Kang
text: A2. We also need to redefine effective leadership and separate style from effectiveness. Being charismatic may not equal effective leader. Many 'feminine' qualities like listening, being collaborative are important leadership skills. #EVELeadershipChat @programmeeve

name: So-Young Kang
text: A2. Some social norms start with very basic things like providing childcare and opp for working moms to continue working. There are cultural norms that have to be redefined. #EVELeadershipChat @programmeeve
